<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-467-590  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 467 590.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  July 24 1989 v3 n30 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Long road to CALS implementation; islands of automation limitusability of resulting data. (Computer-Aided Acquisition andLogistics support)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schaeffer, Barry A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The implementation of Computer-Aided Acquisition and LogisticsSupport (CALS) is hampered by islands of automation wherein agreat deal of time and power are used to solve some local problemsbut the resulting data is hardly useful in areas other than whereit was generated.andP;  CALS seeks to improve the system for weaponsprocurement.andP;  Its objectives are to reduce lead time for weaponssystems deployment, to reduce cost of development and support, andto improve the quality of weapons and their support elements.andP;  Inits attempts to overcome the problem of islands of automation, theCALS staff is seeking to establish a standard for informationinterchange.andP;  It has used the Air Force's Automated TechnicalOrder System as a starting point.andP;  CALS' mandate is far fromachieved, however, because of its meager annual budget of $10million.andP;  Defense establishment stalwarts are not taking theprogram seriously.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Purchasing SystemsWeaponsMilitaryInformation Resources ManagementUnited States. Department of DefenseAutomationStandardization.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>